# OpenShift-Specific Certificate Operations
OpenShift consumes certs in PEM format everywhere. Here's where each type of cert goes.

Ingress / Route TLS
When you create a TLS or re-encrypt route, you supply PEM directly:
#oc create route edge my-route --service=my-svc --cert=server.crt --key=server.key --ca-cert=ca.crt --hostname=app.example.com

For re-encrypt routes (TLS between router and pod):
#oc create route reencrypt my-route \
  --service=my-svc \
  --cert=server.crt \
  --key=server.key \
  --ca-cert=ca.crt \
  --dest-ca-cert=internal-ca.crt \
  --hostname=app.example.com

--dest-ca-cert is the CA that signed the backend pod's certificate — the router uses this to verify the pod.

Default Ingress Controller Certificate (cluster-wide)
To replace the default wildcard cert on *.apps.<cluster>:

# Step 1: Create a secret in openshift-ingress
oc create secret tls custom-ingress-cert \
  --cert=fullchain.crt --key=server.key \
  -n openshift-ingress

# Step 2: Patch the IngressController
oc patch ingresscontroller default -n openshift-ingress-operator \
  --type=merge \
  -p '{"spec":{"defaultCertificate":{"name":"custom-ingress-cert"}}}'

The fullchain.crt should be your server cert concatenated with intermediates:
cat server.crt intermediate.crt > fullchain.crt


API Server Certificate
To set a custom cert for the API endpoint (api.<cluster>):

# Create the secret in openshift-config
oc create secret tls api-cert \
  --cert=fullchain.crt --key=server.key \
  -n openshift-config

# Patch the APIServer resource
oc patch apiserver cluster --type=merge \
  -p '{"spec":{"servingCerts":{"namedCertificates":[{"names":["api.ocp-prod.example.com"],"servingCertificate":{"name":"api-cert"}}]}}}'

Caution: If this cert is wrong or expired, you can lock yourself out of the cluster. Always test the cert chain before applying.

Injecting a Custom CA into the Cluster Trust Bundle
When your internal CA needs to be trusted cluster-wide (so pods can reach internal services with certs signed by your CA):

# Step 1: Create a ConfigMap with your CA cert
oc create configmap custom-ca-bundle \
  --from-file=ca-bundle.crt=ca.crt \
  -n openshift-config

# Step 2: Patch the cluster proxy to reference it
oc patch proxy/cluster --type=merge \
  -p '{"spec":{"trustedCA":{"name":"custom-ca-bundle"}}}'

Once you do this, any ConfigMap in any namespace that carries the label config.openshift.io/inject-trusted-cabundle: "true" will automatically get the merged CA bundle injected:

apiVersion: v1
kind: ConfigMap
metadata:
  name: trusted-ca
  labels:
    config.openshift.io/inject-trusted-cabundle: "true"
data: {}

The cluster network operator merges your custom CA with the system CAs and populates the ca-bundle.crt key. Pods then mount this ConfigMap and point their TLS clients at it.

TLS Secrets for Application Pods
Standard Kubernetes TLS secret — works for any app or operator expecting a cert:

#oc create secret tls my-app-tls \
  --cert=server.crt --key=server.key \
  -n my-namespace

For apps that need PKCS#12 (Java apps on OpenShift, CockroachDB JDBC connections, etc.), you'd create a generic secret with the P12 file:
#oc create secret generic my-app-p12 \
  --from-file=keystore.p12=bundle.p12 \
  --from-literal=keystore-password=changeit \
  -n my-namespace

Part 4: Validation & Debugging Commands
These are invaluable when something isn't working:

# Verify cert matches key (modulus must match)
openssl x509 -noout -modulus -in server.crt | openssl md5
openssl rsa -noout -modulus -in server.key | openssl md5

# Verify full chain
openssl verify -CAfile ca.crt server.crt
openssl verify -CAfile ca.crt -untrusted intermediate.crt server.crt

# Check what a remote server is presenting
openssl s_client -connect app.example.com:443 -showcerts </dev/null 2>/dev/null | openssl x509 -text -noout

# Check cert expiry
openssl x509 -in server.crt -noout -dates

# Check SANs
openssl x509 -in server.crt -noout -ext subjectAltName

# Decode a PKCS#12 to see what's inside
openssl pkcs12 -in bundle.p12 -info -nokeys

# Check from inside a pod on OpenShift
oc exec my-pod -- openssl s_client -connect internal-svc:8443 -CAfile /var/run/secrets/kubernetes.io/serviceaccount/ca.crt </dev/null
```

